  abstract = {Abstract             Recent years have seen severe wildfires in the Northern Hemisphere. This study statistically links atmospheric blocks to extreme fire weather () and observed fires (OF) across seasons from 1979 to 2020. Based on co‐location and odds ratio statistics, we find that a substantial part of  co‐occurs with blocks. In areas where blocks occur regularly, blocks increase the odds of  by a factor of 4–5, with up to a 30‐fold increase locally. The link between blocks and  is stronger at latitudes north of 50N, but exhibits regional and seasonal variations. We also find a significant link between blocks and OF in the Arctic regions during summer. This study reveals new links between atmospheric blocks and wildfire danger.           ,              Plain Language Summary             Atmospheric blocks are persistent and long‐lasting high‐pressure weather systems that can cause heat waves and droughts. We use statistical methods to understand if blocks are also important for wildfire danger and wildfire occurrence in the Northern Hemisphere. We find that blocks increase extreme wildfire danger by a factor of 4–5 in frequently blocked areas, and up to 30 in some Northern Hemisphere regions. We also find a significant though weaker link between blocks and satellite‐observed fires in the Arctic regions during summer. The relationship between blocks and wildfire danger and occurrence varies by season and region but is strongest over the Arctic regions. These results establish a quantitative link between persistent weather patterns and wildfires that might be exploited for sub‐seasonal forecasting. In addition, it demonstrates that atmospheric blocks are important atmospheric processes to increase wildfire danger.           ,              Key Points                                                                Extreme fire weather danger and satellite‐observed fires are frequently co‐located with atmospheric blocks at higher latitudes                