  abstract = {Abstract             The uncertainty of the analysis and the error growth of the forecast from two of the best prediction systems based on radar data assimilation are studied to determine how close we are from accurately forecasting thunderstorms and what additional information would be required to achieve this goal. Even if these two state‐of‐the‐art systems frequently assimilate all available measurements for one, or assimilate radar data every 30~s for the other, considerable uncertainty remains in unobserved atmospheric properties such as temperature or humidity. Worse, limited improvement can be expected as limited direct measurements exist, and essentially all the covariance‐based information is being exploited. Unless a massive investment in new measurement technologies occurs, or radically new ideas are proposed, forecast accuracy will remain insufficient to properly simulate the complete lifetime of a thunderstorm, limiting the accuracy and value of threat forecasting.           ,              Plain Language Summary             Because thunderstorms evolve quickly and generate many threats, a large research community seeks to improve their forecasts. But progress is difficult. To understand why, we studied the quality of the forecasts from two research‐quality systems. We found that we have a considerable challenge in estimating the detailed structure of temperature, humidity, and winds in the atmosphere in and around storms. This then hampers how far in the future we can forecast the evolution of storms and their threats. Our analysis also suggests that we are doing as well as our current measurements and tools allow. Hence, without significantly changing them, progress will remain difficult.           ,              Key Points                                                                Initial conditions derived using two of the best convective‐scale data assimilation systems have considerable errors at storm‐cell scales                                                     These errors severely limit the skillful forecast time of thunderstorms and their threats                                                     A greater variety in observational data sets at higher density would reduce errors at smaller scales},
